        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(discord): expose sender bot status in context",
        "body": "**Prompt request:** Make the Discord channel forward sender bot status into the inbound agent context so an operator running `allowBots` can tell a bot sender from a human, matching what Telegram already exposes, while preserving existing bot detection and PluralKit handling.\n\n## What Problem This Solves\n\nDiscord already detects whether an inbound message was authored by a bot (`author.bot`) and uses that for loop protection, but it never forwards the fact to the agent. With `allowBots: true` (or `\"mentions\"`), a bot-authored message reaches the agent indistinguishable from a human one: the \"Sender (untrusted metadata)\" block in the prompt has no `is_bot` field. Operators wiring bot-to-bot or integration flows on Discord therefore cannot have the agent treat bot senders differently, even though Telegram exposes this today.\n\n## Why This Change Was Made\n\nThe shared inbound context already carries sender bot status end-to-end: `buildChannelInboundEventContext` maps `sender.isBot` to `SenderIsBot`, which renders as `is_bot` in the untrusted sender metadata block. Telegram populates it; Discord computes the same signal (`author.bot`) but does not pass it through. This change forwards that signal into the `sender` object Discord already builds, gated on `!sender.isPluralKit` so PluralKit proxy messages — which post under a bot author but represent a human member — are not reported as bots. No core or SDK change is needed; this PR only changes the Discord adapter's inbound context assembly and its tests.\n\n## User Impact\n\nOperators with `allowBots` enabled now see `\"is_bot\": true` in the untrusted sender metadata for genuine bot-authored Discord messages, letting their agent or system prompt branch on sender type (for example, not auto-replying to other bots). Human messages — including those relayed through PluralKit — are unaffected, and the field is simply absent. There is no change when `allowBots` is off, where bot messages are still filtered as before.\n\n## Evidence\n\nDirect production-path run via `node --import tsx` — real production functions with no mocked I/O, not a vitest or CI run (and not a full live Discord network smoke): the Discord inbound path `buildDiscordMessageProcessContext` and the prompt renderer `buildInboundUserContextPrefix` were invoked directly for a bot author, a human author, and a PluralKit proxy message. Redacted terminal output of the agent-visible `Sender (untrusted metadata)` block:\n\n~~~text\n=== bot author admitted under allowBots ===\nctxPayload.SenderIsBot = true\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n{\n  \"label\": \"Deploy Bot\",\n  \"name\": \"Deploy Bot\",\n  \"username\": \"deploybot\",\n  \"is_bot\": true\n}\n\n=== human author ===\nctxPayload.SenderIsBot = undefined\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n{\n  \"label\": \"Alice\",\n  \"name\": \"Alice\",\n  \"username\": \"alice\"\n}\n\n=== PluralKit proxy (bot author, human member identity) ===\nctxPayload.SenderIsBot = undefined\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n{\n  \"label\": \"Member\",\n  \"name\": \"Member\",\n  \"username\": \"member\",\n  \"tag\": \"member\"\n}\n~~~\n\nThe bot author reaches the agent prompt with `is_bot: true`; the human author and the PluralKit proxy (human member behind a bot author) both omit the field. The same three cases are also asserted by focused unit tests in `message-handler.context.test.ts`.\n",
        "branch": "fix/discord-sender-bot-status",
